According to the world's premier survey of Lithium-ion battery prices, the BloombergNEF, the average price of a battery in 2019 was $156/kWh. This marks an 87 percent decline since the technology was first introduced in 2010. This makes for an average of a 9.6 percent decline per year. [1] Assuming this same rate of decline, we can extrapolate an average price of $141.02/kWh in 2020. But many industry experts, including the Concern of Atomic Scientists, predict that cost-cutting will become more capital intensive in the next decade. [2] For the sake of argument, let's half that decline rate to 4.8 percent. This brings us to an upperbound of $148.52/kWh.

Not sure how to approach, so I started with facts. Since we are relying on this methodology, we start with US$161 as the cost per kWh in 2019. And the decline rate seems to be steady, 16% decline, kind of like a Moore's Law for batteries (which doesn't exist, at least no exponential one). While there's no exact corollary, there has been a trend line in improvement in improving chemistries for production of kWh that helps drives prices per kWh downward, 5-8% (https://www.edn.com/do-lithium-ion-batteries-follow-moores-law/). McKinsey, one of the sources in the spreadsheet provided, made a pretty good estimate back in 2012, that missed, ($200 by 2020, $160 by 2025; a lot once inflation is accounted for) but I thought it was interesting (https://www.mckinsey.com/business-functions/sustainability/our-insights/battery-technology-charges-ahead).
